Normally I wouldnâ€™t do 100% on a prediction but this one is a case where there is pretty much no other sound prediction. When looking at the data from Eurostat, we see that there was an inflation rate of 9.9 last month. Since the data will likely stay the same or increase due to the trends from the last months, it would be pretty much impossible for the annual rate of inflation for the eurozone to go below 5.0%.
According to the EU, the inflation rate is 9.9% in October.

The current eurozone inflation rate is 9.9%. Last month it was 9.1%. This is much higher than 5% which I believe has a 100% chance of being by the deadline. There is no economic way for the inflation rate to drop 5% in less than a week. Therefore, I am predicting a 100% chance that the inflation rate is 5% or more in the eurozone.

Considering the fact that the rate of inflation in the eurozone is about 9%, there is no mathematical way that it will go anywhere near sub-five percent in the next month. There is no feasible way to decrease the inflation rate by such a drastic measure without causing a terrible recession that could put the global economy in the toilet bin. Therefore, this is a very rare example where there is only one prediction that there is no doubt that it will come into fruition.

The current rate sits at 9% and has been on a steady increase all year long. With the state of the individual countries economies, I don't see the Eurozone's inflation rate dropping below 5 percent in the coming weeks.
Given the war in Ukraine and relatively low key interest rates from the European Central Bank and US, I don't think that inflation can be turned around from the 10% it's at now in 2 months.
Given that Germany's inflation reached double digits in Sept, the Eurozone itself is unlikely to be mathematically <6%.

The Eurostat source that will determine the question's outcome shows increasing inflation in every single month of 2022, with the latest reported month (July) at 8.9%. What are the chances that it will soon fall off a cliff and drop to below 5%? Essentially zero, IMHO. But there is virtually no difference in Brier scoring, which is a squared function, between 98% and 100%. So I'll keep a couple of chips on the next bin down.

I just read an inflation thread on twitter, outlining demand, supply, goods and services elements. I have also been following John Authers' daily emails most of which have been covering how transitory inflation is. The ECB itself thinks inflation will falls back to 2% by the end of 2022 which is a significant fall. There do seem to be reasons to expect a decline as supply chain bottlenecks and energy could reasonably be expected to ease. It is unclear how much wage pressure will then feed into keeping inflation elevated next year and whether reduced QE would offset this (the ECB is continuing QE unlike other central banks) and so generally is doing less to moderate inflation. This is currently difficult to forecast...

Inflation across the 19-member eurozone soared to 4.9% in November, outstripping City forecasts and putting pressure on the European Central Bank to review its policy of ultra-low interest rates. _________________________ There is not yet a consensus on what caused inflation to run high. Some mention the supplies chains and the switch by consumers to favor goods over a different type of spending (travel). If that is the case things should get back to normal soon enough.

Looking at the 25 year graph for the inflation rate in the eurozone there are no examples of inflation spiking to the 'extreme' degree it is right now (https://tradingeconomics.com/euro-area/inflation-cpi). Of course that is because it is relatively stable only leaving the 0-3% range a handful of times since its inception. The outside view is therefore that we will return to this mean and see the rate fall below 3%, probably between 0 and 2%. The current rate is also exacerbated by the much lower than usual inflation a year ago, leading to perhaps misleading annualised figures. However if this was the only cause we would expect to see it decelerating.

So far we have 1 of the 12 months reported, at a 0.5% month-over-month increase (https://tradingeconomics.com/euro-area/inflation-rate-mom). If this increase were to hold constant we would be at 6.2% annual increase.
